This is a sophisticated direction. You are correct—styles like **Cyberpunk 2077**, **Glassmorphism**, or **Neumorphism** cannot be reduced to simple variable swaps. They require structural changes, pseudo-elements, filters, and keyframe animations (the "Style Powers").

Here is the **Revised Technical Specification (v2)** based on your feedback.

### 1. Data Architecture: The "Style Cartridge" Pattern

We will deprecate the simple `DESIGN_PRESETS` array. Instead, we will treat each style as a "Cartridge" that plugs into the system.

**The Contract (`lib/styles/types.ts`):**
To support "Style Powers" (effects, animations, unique shapes), the definition must be flexible.

```typescript
export interface StyleCartridge {
  id: string; // e.g., 'cyberpunk'
  meta: DesignPreset; // Reusing existing metadata (label, tags, etc.)

  // The "Soul" of the style
  previewConfig: {
    // 1. Semantic Tokens (The Variables)
    // We inject these into the Mannequin's root container.
    theme: {
      '--bg-layer-1': string;
      '--bg-layer-2': string;
      '--text-primary': string;
      '--accent-color': string;
      '--border-radius': string;
      '--font-display': string;
    };

    // 2. The "Power" (Raw CSS Injection)
    // This allows keyframes, clip-paths, backdrop-filters, and pseudo-elements.
    // We will scope this using a unique ID to prevent style bleeding.
    injectCss?: string; 

    // 3. Structural Overrides (Tailwind Classes)
    // Sometimes a style needs specific layout tweaks (e.g., uppercase text, tracking-widest)
    elementClasses: {
      container?: string;
      header?: string;
      card?: string;
      buttonPrimary?: string;
      input?: string;
      badge?: string;
    };
  };

  // The Zero-Gen Pre-calculated Spec (Optional/Fallback)
  standardSpec?: string; 
}
```

### 2. The Visualization Engine: `<StyleMannequin />`

This component is the "Stage" where the Cartridge is loaded.

*   **Isolation:** It will generate a unique ID for the container (e.g., `#preview-root-cyberpunk`).
*   **Injection:** It renders a `<style>` tag *inside* the component that injects `previewConfig.injectCss`, scoping all selectors to that ID (e.g., `#preview-root-cyberpunk .btn-primary { ... }`).
*   **Structure:** It renders a standardized UI layout (Title, Card, Primary Action, Input, Tags) so the user can compare apples-to-apples across styles.

### 3. The Interaction Model: `StyleInspectorModal`

We will abandon the sidebar for the "Inspection" phase.

*   **Trigger:** Clicking a Grid Card opens the Modal.
*   **Layout (60/40 Split):**
    *   **Left (60%):** The `<StyleMannequin />`. A large, immersive canvas showing the style in action (live CSS, no images).
    *   **Right (40%):** The Configuration Panel.
        *   **Toggle:** "Tailored Project" vs "Standard Library".
        *   **Context:** Textarea (visible only in Tailored mode).
        *   **Typography:** Font picker.
        *   **Action:** "Ignite Kiln" button.

### 4. Implementation Strategy: The "Pilot" Approach

To ensure scalability and avoid token limits:

1.  **Refactor Phase:** I will set up the folder structure (`lib/styles/registry.ts`) and the `StyleMannequin` component.
2.  **Migration Phase:** I will port **ALL** existing styles to the new format, but initialized with a **"Base Theme"**.
3.  **Enhancement Phase (Pilot):** I will manually code the high-fidelity `injectCss` and `tokens` for **3 specific styles** (Cyberpunk, Neumorphism, and Minimal) to demonstrate the engine's power.
    *   *Why?* This keeps the update size manageable and prevents the app from breaking. You can then incrementally "upgrade" other styles by editing their specific files later.

### 5. Fallback Logic

For the **Standard Spec** feature:
*   We will default to **"Just-In-Time Generation"**.
*   Since we don't have the pre-written MD files yet, the "Standard Library" mode will trigger a specific API call to Gemini with a system prompt optimized for generic specs (as discussed previously).
*   This satisfies "select fallback for now" while setting up the UI to support instant loading in the future.

**Are we aligned on this architecture? Shall I begin the implementation with Phase 1 (Data Layer & Mannequin)?**

This is the correct mental model. We are moving from a "Configuration" mindset to a **"Component Architecture"** mindset.

Here is my Point of View (POV) on how we execute this **"Exposed Anatomy"** strategy to ensure maximum flexibility for styles like Cyberpunk, Glassmorphism, or Brutalism.

### 1. The Anatomy (The Fixed Skeleton)

The `<StyleMannequin />` will not just be a bunch of divs. It will be a rigorously defined DOM structure with **semantic class hooks**. Every style relies on this consistent skeleton.

We will expose these specific classes. A style can choose to style them, ignore them, or completely transform them using CSS transforms/pseudo-elements.

```html
<!-- The Root Stage (Scoped ID) -->
<div id="preview-[id]" class="ds-stage">

  <!-- The Main Container/Card -->
  <div class="ds-panel">

    <!-- Header Section -->
    <div class="ds-header">
      <div class="ds-status-indicator"></div> <!-- For glowing dots/status lights -->
      <h3 class="ds-title">System Ready</h3>
      <span class="ds-tag">v4.1</span>
    </div>

    <!-- Content Area -->
    <div class="ds-body">
      <p class="ds-text-muted">Initiating visual sequence...</p>

      <!-- Input Group -->
      <div class="ds-field-wrapper">
        <label class="ds-label">Command</label>
        <div class="ds-input-container">
           <input class="ds-input" placeholder="Enter data..." />
           <div class="ds-input-decorator"></div> <!-- For underlines/icons -->
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <!-- Action Row -->
    <div class="ds-actions">
      <button class="ds-btn ds-btn-secondary">Cancel</button>
      <button class="ds-btn ds-btn-primary">
        <span class="ds-btn-text">Confirm</span>
        <div class="ds-btn-glow"></div> <!-- For internal glows/effects -->
      </button>
    </div>

  </div>

  <!-- Decorative Elements (Background blobs, grid lines) -->
  <div class="ds-deco-layer"></div>
</div>
```

### 2. The Cartridge (The Implementation)

Instead of just "configuring variables", a Style Definition becomes a **CSS Injector**.

**Example: How `Cyberpunk` utilizes the Anatomy**
It doesn't just change colors. It targets the classes to reshape the geometry.

```typescript
// lib/styles/catalog/modern/cyberpunk.ts

export const cyberpunkStyle: StyleDefinition = {
  id: 'cyberpunk',
  // ... metadata ...
  preview: {
    // 1. Dynamic Variables (Infinite gradients/colors allowed)
    vars: {
      '--accent': '#f0f',
      '--bg': '#000',
      '--clip-path-btn': 'polygon(0 0, 100% 0, 100% 70%, 90% 100%, 0 100%)'
    },

    // 2. Raw CSS Power (The Logic)
    // This is where we target the "Exposed Anatomy"
    css: `
      .ds-panel {
        border: 2px solid var(--accent);
        background: 
          repeating-linear-gradient(
            45deg, 
            rgba(0,0,0,0.8), 
            rgba(0,0,0,0.8) 10px, 
            rgba(20,20,20,0.8) 10px, 
            rgba(20,20,20,0.8) 20px
          );
        box-shadow: 4px 4px 0px var(--accent); /* Hard shadow */
      }

      .ds-btn-primary {
        clip-path: var(----clip-path-btn); /* Geometric shape */
        text-transform: uppercase;
        letter-spacing: 2px;
      }

      /* Using the exposed decorator for a scanline effect */
      .ds-deco-layer {
        background-image: linear-gradient(rgba(18, 16, 16, 0) 50%, rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.25) 50%), linear-gradient(90deg, rgba(255, 0, 0, 0.06), rgba(0, 255, 0, 0.02), rgba(0, 0, 255, 0.06));
        background-size: 100% 2px, 3px 100%;
        pointer-events: none;
      }
    `
  }
}
```

**Example: How `Glassmorphism` utilizes the SAME Anatomy**

```typescript
export const glassStyle: StyleDefinition = {
  // ...
  preview: {
    css: `
      .ds-stage {
        /* Vibrant background blob */
        background: radial-gradient(circle at 10% 20%, rgb(255, 131, 131) 0%, rgb(110, 130, 250) 90%);
      }

      .ds-panel {
        /* The Glass Effect */
        background: rgba(255, 255, 255, 0.25);
        backdrop-filter: blur(12px);
        border: 1px solid rgba(255, 255, 255, 0.3);
        border-radius: 24px;
        box-shadow: 0 8px 32px 0 rgba(31, 38, 135, 0.15);
      }

      .ds-btn-primary {
        background: rgba(255,255,255, 0.4);
        /* ... */
      }
    `
  }
}
```

### 3. The Interaction Flow

1.  **Grid View Update**:
    *   Add a subtle "Eye" icon button to the top-right of every card (floating).
    *   Hovering the card engages the existing card hover state.
    *   Clicking the **Eye** opens the **Inspector Modal**.
    *   Clicking the **Body** of the card selects it (as it does now) and opens the sidebar (or we can unify this into the modal as you prefer, but "Eye" specifically implies "Just looking").

2.  **The Inspector Modal**:
    *   **Left Side (The Mannequin)**: Renders the `ds-stage` with the injected CSS from the selected cartridge.
    *   **Right Side (The Controls)**:
        *   **Standard Spec Toggle**: "I just want the generic spec" (No Context needed).
        *   **Context Mode**: "I want to tailor this" (Input field appears).
        *   **Generate Button**: Fires the API.

This approach gives us the "Power" you asked for. We aren't just swapping variables; we are swapping the entire rendering logic while keeping the DOM structure constant.

**Ready for your signal.**
